title: Hidden Setting: Resilient Render
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki
caption: Resilient Render

<<.from-version "5.4.x">> `$:/config/ResilientRender`

By default, a widget that throws an exception while rendering or refreshing aborts the whole render tree — a single faulty widget can blank an entire tiddler or, in an interactive interface, the page. When this setting is `yes`, such a throw is //contained//: the failing widget degrades to a `<span class="tc-error">` message and its sibling widgets keep rendering.

|!Value |!Behaviour |
|(unset) or `no` |Exceptions propagate (//fail-loud//). Recommended for server-side, CI and static-site builds, which should fail visibly on a broken tiddler. This is the default. |
|`yes` |A throwing widget degrades in place to a `tc-error` span; siblings still render; the same protection applies on refresh. |

!! How it works

The boundary lives in the `Widget` base class (`renderChildren` and `refreshChildren`) via a shared `containChildError` helper. On a contained throw the failing child widget is `destroy()`ed — clearing any partial DOM and event listeners — and replaced in the widget tree by the error widget, so destroy, refresh and sibling DOM positioning stay consistent. The refresh path captures the DOM anchor before destroying the child.

`TranscludeRecursionError` is never contained — it always propagates, so the transclusion recursion guard keeps working. Contained errors are logged via `$tw.utils.warning`. The setting is read only when an exception is actually thrown, so there is no cost on the normal render or refresh path.

!! When to enable

Interactive, embedded and live-update interfaces — and headless engines that render into a host DOM — benefit from containing a single faulty widget rather than losing the whole view. Leave it off for build pipelines that should fail loud.

!! Example

See [[Resilient Rendering (Example)]].
